---
<Pillar
  title="Is My ZIP Next"
  description="State-by-state homeowners insurance risk explainers for high-risk US states."
  intro="You haven't been non-renewed yet, but you can see the trend in your state. Pick your state below for a structured rundown — carriers leaving, residual market, top hazards, regulator response, and what to do this month."
>
  <h2>How to read these pages</h2>
  <p>Every state page below follows the same ten-section structure — non-renewal data, carriers leaving, the residual market option, top hazards, regulator actions, fortification programs, what homeowners are reporting, and three things to do this month. Identical structure on purpose: it lets you compare your state against a neighbor's in minutes, and it makes gaps obvious when one state has no answer where another does.</p>
  <p>Each page carries a severity badge — <strong>critical</strong>, <strong>high</strong>, or <strong>elevated</strong>. The badge measures one thing: how hard it is for a homeowner to find and keep coverage in that state right now. It is not a hazard ranking. Montana burns more acres than Florida, but Florida's insurance market is in far worse shape, and the badges reflect that. We re-rate every state when we refresh the statistics each quarter.</p>
  <p>The two cross-state articles at the bottom cover machinery that doesn't respect state lines: the risk scores insurers buy to decide who gets dropped, and the State Farm California drawdown that previews how a large-carrier exit unfolds.</p>

  <h2>State pages</h2>
  <ul class="state-list">
    {states.map((s) => (
      <li>
        <a href={`/is-my-zip-next/${s.slug}/`}><strong>{s.name}</strong></a> — {s.hook}
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>Cross-state articles</h2>
